This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it presents a new approach for motion segmentation in indoor scenes using event-based learning and introduces a new dataset for this purpose. The paper also mentions the use of neural networks, which is a common technique in computer vision research. 

The paper is also likely to belong to the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category as it mentions the suitability of the proposed approach for scene constrained robotics applications. 

The paper may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category as it uses a neural network architecture for event-based learning. 

The paper may belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category as it presents a new approach for object segmentation and motion estimation, which are important tasks in AI. 

Finally, the paper may belong to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category as it uses a neural network architecture for event-based learning.
